Looking at Passage 2, Bryan's central argument is that people naturally resist foreign domination and that the Filipinos (and other island peoples) would inevitably protest and resist American rule. He emphasizes that "God himself...placed in every human heart the love of liberty" and that no race "would welcome a foreign master."

Bryan directly states that "the subject races" would "protest against such a policy and to resist to the extent of their ability." He argues this resistance is natural and inevitable, citing historical examples of American leaders who fought against foreign rule.

Beveridge's vision in Passage 1 presents an optimistic picture of Americans bringing civilization and prosperity to these territories, seemingly assuming the islanders would welcome or accept American governance. Bryan would view this as naive because it fails to account for the natural human desire for self-governance and the inevitable resistance that would follow.
